# History: pr-enumeration-discovery-idempotency

This file preserves the full original content of every skill merged into the
`pr-enumeration-discovery-idempotency` canonical.

## v1.3.0 (2026-06-15)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus session triaging #1367/#1199/#1193 — 2 of 3 were zombie issues
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Extended the `## When to Use` triggers with two new bullets:
  - You are handed "open issues to solve" (human/agent) — verify each on
    `origin/main` FIRST; an issue can be a ZOMBIE whose closing PR already
    merged (GitHub didn't auto-close or it was a duplicate). Re-implementing
    a zombie is the duplicate-PR anti-pattern. `gh issue list` is a
    point-in-time snapshot — re-check `gh issue view N` before acting.
  - A local `<issue>-auto-impl` branch looks like it holds the right commits
    but has a SHA mismatch vs `origin/<branch>` and a revert-shaped multi-file
    diff — it's on a stale pre-merge base. An `add/add` cherry-pick conflict
    proves the file already exists on main.
- Added 3 new `## Failed Attempts` rows:
  - Started implementing an "open" issue without checking if it was already
    merged (nearly re-implemented zombies #1367 and #1193).
  - Trusted the initial `gh issue list` snapshot for the whole session
    (#1193 closed mid-session by #1376 but the stale snapshot showed it open).
  - Tried to reuse a local `1193-auto-impl` branch that appeared to hold the
    right 2 commits but reverted the merged #1358/#1361 decomposition.
- Added new `## Verified On` row: operator-side zombie-issue triage of
  #1367/#1199/#1193 (only #1199 was real work → PR #1377, merged green).
- Updated the Overview `Outcome` line to mention the v1.3.0
  operator/agent-side complement.
- Frontmatter: `version: "1.2.0"` → `"1.3.0"`, `date` stays `2026-06-15`,
  new tags `zombie-issue`, `verify-on-main-first`,
  `gh-issue-list-snapshot-stale`, `stale-branch-base`,
  `add-add-cherry-pick-conflict`.
- Description: added items (12) zombie-issue / verify-on-main-first triggers
  and (13) the stale `<issue>-auto-impl` branch / `add/add` conflict trigger.

### Why

A user asked "there are three open issues left, lets solve them" (#1367,
#1199, #1193 in ProjectHephaestus). Investigation found TWO of the three were
ZOMBIES — already implemented and merged, the issue just never auto-closed:

- #1367 was a duplicate of #1368; #1368's fix (PR #1372) was already merged to
  `main`. Every acceptance criterion was verified satisfied on `origin/main`
  (grepped the `log_on_error` param in `github/client.py` + the two regression
  tests). Action: closed #1367 as duplicate — NO code, NO PR.
- #1193 had been implemented and merged via TWO PRs (#1282 on 2026-06-15,
  #1376 on 2026-06-16), both carrying a valid `Closes #1193`. The
  ReviewerProtocol + abstract `BaseReviewer.run` were live on `main`. #1376
  auto-closed the issue mid-session — but the initial `gh issue list` snapshot
  (taken minutes earlier) still showed it OPEN. Action: confirmed
  live-on-main, no work.
- Only #1199 (markdownlint duplicate-job consolidation) was genuine remaining
  work → one signed PR #1377, merged.

A local branch `1193-auto-impl` LOOKED like it held the 2 relevant commits
(feat: ReviewerProtocol, fix: ABC contract), but its full diff vs main was a
28-file MONSTER that REVERTED the merged decomposition work (#1358/#1361) — it
was built on a stale pre-decomposition base. The cherry-pick hit an `add/add`
conflict on `test_interfaces.py`, which was itself PROOF the file already
existed on main. A SHA mismatch between local `1193-auto-impl` and
`origin/1193-auto-impl` was the first red flag.

This is the SAME duplicate-PR-churn root cause as the automation-side triggers
(10)-(11), but seen from the human/agent operator side. Lesson: before
implementing any "open issue", verify ground truth on `origin/main` first — the
issue may be a zombie. Re-implementing a zombie is the exact duplicate-PR
anti-pattern the automation-side triggers exist to prevent.

